  <section id="insurance-options">
    <h2>Insurance Options for Retirees</h2>
    <p>
      Insurance for Italy retirement involves two phases: visa-compliant coverage for initial application and residence, then potentially adding SSN enrollment after your first permit renewal. Understanding both phases helps you plan effectively.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>International health insurance</strong> is required for visa application and provides comprehensive coverage from day one. Plans must meet Schengen standards (€30,000+ medical coverage, repatriation coverage) and Italian consulate expectations (comprehensive coverage, not travel insurance). The insurers recommended below all meet these requirements.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>SSN enrollment</strong> becomes available after your first permesso renewal (typically after 1-2 years). By paying approximately €400/year (subject to income-based adjustment), you join Italy's public healthcare system. SSN covers most care including hospitalizations, specialist visits, and prescriptions with small copays. Many retirees maintain both SSN enrollment and private insurance.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Private insurance after SSN:</strong> Even with SSN access, many retirees keep international insurance. Reasons include: shorter wait times for specialists, private hospital room options, choice of specific doctors, and coverage for care outside Italy (SSN covers limited emergency care in other EU countries only). The combination provides maximum flexibility.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Pre-existing conditions:</strong> Italian consulates evaluate insurance coverage, not health status. However, your insurer's underwriting determines whether pre-existing conditions are covered. Moratorium underwriting (conditions excluded initially, then covered after claim-free period) or full underwriting with condition-specific terms are common approaches.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="recommended-providers">
    <h2>Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
    <p>
      These international insurers provide coverage that meets Italian visa requirements and offers comprehensive protection for retirees. All are Schengen-compliant and experienced with Italy residency applications.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is well-established with Italian consulates and offers moratorium underwriting for pre-existing conditions. Their European plan provides comprehensive coverage throughout the Schengen area at competitive rates for seniors up to 74.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Allianz Worldwide Care</strong> accepts new members up to 75—the highest limit—and provides excellent coverage quality after full underwriting. Being a European insurer, they're familiar with Italian requirements and provide smooth documentation for visa applications.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Aetna International</strong> offers strong comprehensive coverage with good relationships with Italian private hospitals. Their age limits are lower for new enrollees (64 standard, 69 with existing coverage), but those who qualify get excellent protection.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>IMG Global</strong> provides competitive pricing for healthy retirees. They're a solid choice for those without significant pre-existing conditions who want comprehensive coverage at lower premiums. Pre-existing condition coverage is limited, so they work best for healthy applicants.
    </p>
  </section>

