  <section id="healthcare-system">
    <h2>Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Italy's Servizio Sanitario Nazionale is a universal healthcare system providing comprehensive coverage to residents. Once enrolled (after your first permit renewal), you access the same system Italians use. Quality is generally high, though experiences vary by region and facility.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Public hospitals</strong> handle emergencies, hospitalizations, and major procedures. Large teaching hospitals in cities like Rome, Milan, Florence, and Bologna offer cutting-edge care. Emergency rooms treat everyone regardless of insurance status. Quality is solid—Italy has excellent health outcomes—though facilities may feel older than new American hospitals.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Regional variation:</strong> Northern Italy generally has better-funded, more efficient healthcare than the South. Emilia-Romagna, Lombardy, and Veneto are considered excellent. Southern regions vary more—some facilities are excellent, others underfunded. This affects both SSN care and private options, so consider healthcare when choosing your region.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Wait times:</strong> The SSN has wait times for non-urgent specialist appointments and procedures—sometimes weeks or months. Private insurance provides faster access through private clinics and doctors. Many Italians use private care for convenience while keeping SSN for major hospitalizations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> Italy has extensive pharmacy networks with knowledgeable pharmacists. Generic medications are widely available and inexpensive. Under SSN, most prescriptions have small copays (€1-4). Even without SSN, medication costs are much lower than in the US.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>English availability:</strong> Doctors in major cities often speak some English, especially in private practice. In smaller towns and public hospitals, Italian is essential. Having a translator for complex medical discussions is prudent if your Italian is limited.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs">
    <h2>Cost Planning</h2>
    <p>
      Italy's costs vary dramatically by region. Northern cities like Milan are expensive; southern villages can be remarkably affordable. Understanding regional differences helps you match lifestyle expectations with budget realities.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Total monthly budget</strong> for comfortable retirement ranges from €2,200-4,000 depending heavily on location. A modest Puglia retirement might cost €2,200-2,800; Florence or Rome retirement runs €3,500-4,500+. Insurance costs are relatively consistent regardless of location.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Insurance cost strategies:</strong> Initially, you need comprehensive international insurance (~€5,000-10,000/year for seniors). After SSN enrollment becomes available, some retirees reduce private coverage to a lighter policy while relying more on SSN for routine care. Others maintain full coverage for maximum flexibility.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Regional cost differences:</strong> Southern Italy offers the lowest costs but also less developed infrastructure and healthcare. Central Tuscany/Umbria balances cost and quality. Northern cities cost most but provide the most services. Many retirees settle in smaller cities (Perugia, Lecce, Siena) for quality at moderate costs.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Currency exposure:</strong> Euro-denominated expenses mean exchange rate fluctuations affect USD income purchasing power. The dollar-euro rate has ranged from near parity to 1.20+ in recent years—a significant budget impact. Planning for this variability is prudent.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mt-6">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Can I rely on SSN instead of private insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Not initially—private insurance is required for visa application and first years of residency. After SSN enrollment becomes available, some retirees scale back private coverage, but most maintain both for flexibility and shorter wait times.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What income do I actually need for the visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Officially unspecified, but practical experience suggests €31,000-40,000/year for singles, €38,000-50,000/year for couples. Higher income strengthens applications. Consulates evaluate holistically—pension stability matters alongside amount.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How does the 1-euro house program work?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Depopulating villages sell abandoned houses for €1 but require significant renovation commitments (often €20,000-50,000+). It's not a cheap housing hack—it's a commitment to restore historic properties. Healthcare in these villages is limited.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Italian language essential?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">More than in some expat destinations. While tourist areas have English speakers, daily life—bureaucracy, healthcare, neighbors—requires Italian. Most successful retirees learn conversational Italian. This enriches the experience significantly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Can I use Italian healthcare while traveling in Europe?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">SSN provides an EHIC (European Health Insurance Card) for emergency care in other EU countries—but only emergency care, not routine treatment. International insurance provides fuller coverage for travel throughout Europe.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What's the path to Italian citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Standard naturalization requires 10 years of legal residence. For those with Italian ancestry (jure sanguinis), citizenship by descent may be available regardless of residence. Citizenship provides EU citizenship benefits including unrestricted residence anywhere in the EU.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Plan Your Italy Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers experienced with Italian visa requirements. Coverage meets Schengen standards with options for pre-existing conditions."
    buttonText="Get Your Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />
</PageShell>
